<title>UK: Megamergers change top 10 insurance brokers-report.</title>
<headline>Megamergers change top 10 insurance brokers-report.</headline>
<dateline>LONDON 1997-07-22</dateline>
<text>
<p>Acquisitions by insurance brokers Marsh &amp; McLennan and Aon have put them leagues ahead of their other top ten rivals, according to a U.S. insurance magazine.</p>
<p>The annual broker survey by Business Insurance says Marsh &amp; McLennan's acquisition of Johnson &amp; Higgins and CECAR, and Aon's acquisition of Alexander &amp; Alexander, Bain Hogg Group and Minet, mean five of last year's top 20 brokers have disappeared.</p>
<p>A 44 percent increase in gross revenues to $5.45 billion means Marsh &amp; McLennan retains its position as largest broker. Aon's 129.5 percent increase to $3.96 billion, secures second place.</p>
<p>Also in the top 10 are two other newly amalgamated groups, Jardine Lloyd Thompson which has moved to 6th position from 10th last year, and Lambert Fenchurch which moves from 16th to 10th.</p>
<p>The two broking firms which have resisted mergers, Sedgwick and Willis Corroon are third and fourth largest firms respectively.</p>
